<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Your lack of support for our nation and our nation's leader has me awestruck.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
-- Vatikus quotes<br>
<br>
The way I see it, division makes us stronger in ways we can't always anticipate. Debating in a public forum reinforces freedoms we may take for granted from time to time. In the end, one side will lose the pro/anti-war argument, but in the process, as individuals, we will be that much stronger for it. (How in the world did we survive that Civil War?!)<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>I don't care if you didn't vote for Bush, and I don't care if you don't like his decisions, but as a citizen of the United States of America you had better fucking support him.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Will my lack of support pave the way for the apocalypse, make oil prices pierce the stratosphere? What major catastrophe will befall the US if I decide to pick up a sign and join an anti-war demonstration march? For someone who is on the “right” side of the war issue, you, like others, make it sound like the Bill of Rights could not survive an angry shout in an otherwise peaceful assembly. You elevate a difference of opinion to an act of treason when dissidence is exactly what the Constitution encourages to check powers.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Whether you like it or not, he is our Leader, and if he leads me into a battle that I may not agree on I will fight. Just like I would fight for my family.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
You know…I bet a lot of “other sides” believe exactly the same thing. We don’t need to let our conscious dabble in issues of right and wrong, cause and effect, as long as we stay nearsighted.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>You want to be shown proof of every thing in order to have your support. You walk around in this bubble chanting to yourselves that everything is going to be alright, and we can ignore the growing threat to our nation and nothing will happen because there is an ocean in between us. Who is naive now?</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
I don’t need proof. Regardless of whether or not Saddam is keeping nuclear/biological weapons he needs a killing for all the other crimes he has committed against humanity. Saddam isn’t going to march out there in all his glory and meet us head-on, though. He’d likely bunker down beneath a hospital, in a city. I won’t even ask for a count on the percentage of you pro-war people who think it’s just justifiable to kill citizens to eliminate the threat. It’s also the aftermath that gives me pause, like Quts elaborated on. (I’d agree with you more often Quts if I could figure out WTF you’re saying half the time.) To top it off, killing Saddam will NOT eliminate international terrorist activity (emphasis on i-n-t-e-r-n-a-t-i-o-n-a-l). Personally I’d rather slake my thirst for revenge with bin Laden than have a president redirect my rage to settle and old score of his.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>How many of you college students accept financial aid while you march down the street chanting how fucking wrong your country is?<br>
<br>
All of you that ignorantly disapprove of a war with Iraq because it is supposedly based on solely on oil don’t drive fucking cars, use plastics, or use any petroleum products whatsoever, correct?</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
-- Pottz<br>
<br>
Don’t give me that shit Pottz. I’ve crawled under wire, gotten mud packed in places I did not know existed before in the process, and shrieked in the shower, tears springing to my eyes, from blisters the size of boils on my feet, and managed to earn a Navy Achievement Medal, among other awards, in my six-year enlistment. Disagreement, even outrage, is NOT A PRECURSER for anti-nationalism.<br>
<br>
As for petroleum-based products, a large part of why we are still dependent on foreign countries for oil has to do with relentless lobbying from gasoline industries. (Does that make me a big industry hater too?) The lack of financial support from the government to automobile companies for researching increased fuel efficiency is depressing. Toyota and Honda have taken the lead with their hybrid cars, but they break down too much, and the average consumer may find the MSRP high. Good thing, though, Toyota plans to expand the hybrid concept to their other vehicles, and perhaps the cost of manufacturing them will level off. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub54.ezboard.com/bquelliousquaterstherebirth.showUserPublicProfile?gid=varro@quelliousquaterstherebirth>Varro</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Froglok</span><br>  Posts: 10<br> <font color=#00CCFF>(1/20/03 7:43:40 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub54.ezboard.com/fquelliousquaterstherebirthfrm13.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=795.topic&index=183>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re:OT - Opposed to the war with Iraq? Heres what you can do</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.cnn.com/2002/ALLPOLITICS/10/09/iraq.congress/index.html">www.cnn.com/2002/ALLPOLIT...index.html</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
I'm just gonna pick a few points:<br>
<br>
Maybe I missed it if this has already come up, but the above article mentions the CIA directors belief that the real threat is in backing Saddam into a corner where he will almost definately use and distribute weapons of mass destruction.<br>
<br>
If UN resolution violations are a reason for war, then we should go attack Isreal.<br>
<br>
I can't believe a right winger quoted Locke (one of the founders of classical liberalism), and then questioned criticism of national leadership.  How about you read the whole book next time.  I've read Locke way too man times (stupid political science major!!!).  <br>
<br>
Criticism of the government is one of the fundamental rights granted in the first amendment to the constitution.  Do you think the founders followed the king absolutely? bwahahahahaha!!  I will always critique our nations behavior and consider it my patriotic duty to do so.  Those who cry patriotism and don't critically analyse government policy are simple nationalists.  (You remember nationalism right? that thing that is a key component to fascism?)  <br>
<br>
While the US must do all in its power to protect itself, war should be the last resort.  Inspections may seem inane, but if our intelligence is really so conclusive, then maybe it will be able to do something.  According to my military intervention instructor, Isreal is on record as saying it will defend itself against attack unlike in the Gulf War, and Bush has agreed that they have the right.  If Isreal is brought into a conflict with an arab state, be prepared for the possibility of escalation.  <br>
<br>
Say we defeat Saddam and remove him from power, then what?   The majority of the Iraqi population is Shiite and a simple democratic system would probably give rise to Shiite dominance and create a very strong ally to Iran.  <br>
<br>
This is not the Gulf war with a coalition of nations and unprecedented support from Arab states.  Though I'm somewhat underwhelmed by Iraqs military strength (as witnessed in their uncoordinated efforts during desert storm), a ground war into Baghdad will not be a cake walk, especially without greater land rights support to allow a better deployment strategy.  <br>
<br>
We may be headed towards a protracted conflict with possibility of multinational escalation.  This conflict may create the environment that causes Saddam to use and spread the WMD's we're currently so worried about.  Let us try to disarm Iraq through international means in conjunction with our intelligence.  At least we should attempt to disarm as much as possible before going to war.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub54.ezboard.com/bquelliousquaterstherebirth.showUserPublicProfile?gid=feadornlifegiver>Feadorn Lifegiver</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Tolapumj wanna-be</span><br>  Posts: 156<br> <font color=#00CCFF>(1/20/03 9:49:20 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub54.ezboard.com/fquelliousquaterstherebirthfrm13.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=795.topic&index=184>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Re:OT - Opposed to the war with Iraq? Heres what you can</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Maybe I missed it if this has already come up, but the above article mentions the CIA directors belief that the real threat is in backing Saddam into a corner where he will almost definately use and distribute weapons of mass destruction.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
