There have been money links from Saddam and a number of Al-Queda aligned/supporting groups, and direct meetings between Iraqi officials and 9-11 suicide bombers... some of them in Iraq.<br>
<br>
Now, would Saddam likely to be convicted in a U.S. court of law were he a citizen of the US?  Not likely, it's mostly circumstantial.   This isn't analogous to a domestic court issue. <br>
<br>
There is one reason we aren't as militarily mobile vs North Korea right now as Iraq.  China.  China and NK aren't at the high point of their relations, but they still have enough ties that China could very well intervene if we move to fast.   Of course &quot;too fast&quot; is relative... the Iraq weapons issue is 12 years old.  So we are already moving a lot faster on NK than we have on Iraq.<br>
<br>
You mention we found &quot;only&quot; a few dozen empty chemical warheads and the like.. realize the conditions of the inspection team.  They give advance notice (in terms of days) of where they will search, and they are then escorted there by Iraqi chaperones.   Up until JUST recently the whole thing was a giant joke.... one of the big fusses Iraq had was when we insisted the lead time we give them for inspections was reduced to a few days rather than 10 days plus.  Heck Iraq was pretty pissed when we demanded to have more control over where we checked and what was off limits as well.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.sluggy.com/daily.php?date=021009">www.sluggy.com/daily.php?date=021009</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
That pretty much sums up the last decade of US inspections of Iraq.<br>
<br>
The fact that with a few days notices, and armed Iraqi escort the STILL manage to find anything incriminating *at all* is rather disturbing.   <p>Gurunt Bangoo &lt;Wraith&gt;<br>
