Look, if you just want to kick some ass, that's cool, everyone feels aggressive now and then, and this is no less true of nations than of individuals.  Or additionally, argue that it is simply in the geopolitical-economic interests of the US to secure a stronger hold over the enrgy resources of the Middle East.  <br>
<br>
But please, stop with the &quot;seven degrees of separation&quot; sob story theories &quot;But But!! Saddam killed lots of mommies and daddies on 9-11 because someone in another intelligence agency is rumored to have heard an Iraqi was in the same town as Mohammed Atta!!&quot;  If you think ANY serious geopolitical strategist gives a fuck about dying mommies and daddies, and would let such sob stories influence their sheer power and control mindsets, you are just too naive.  Real global politics are about power, first, power, second, and finally, power, third.  The only people who believe the sob story covers the press feeds the benumbed wankers who sit in front of their tv's pounding their fist and their beers are aforementioned benumbed wankers, and prolly President Dubya, who is basically a &quot;Joe Millionaire&quot; in the political realm, a cruel cruel joke the American people have willed on themselves: he claims to be a leader, but he is really just a benumbed wanker who believes the little stories the real players feed to him like lullabies to a baby.<br>
<br>
Hey, and observe: you don't even know if I support military action or not.  But I do know the difference between reality and tv-sob-story-propaganda.  We are not going after Saddam cuz he killed someone's mommy.  We are going after him because he is vulnerable to be knocked off and he sits astride a valuable geopolitical and economic power nexus that our power-fuckers want to fuck long, hard, and deep.  The rest of you keep dreaming your little dreams on your moral la-z-boys about sad puppy dogs and how Saddam does not like apple pie.  I'll live in the rather more brutal, and far less morally smug, world of real politik.<br>
